the signing of the Road Map on the resolution of the conflict in the country. The Road Map proposes that a “Transitional Government of National Unity be established based on a period of two years to conduct the Transitional Interim Period”. Under the Road Map an array of measures is expected to be undertaken to give effect to these objectives: including, but not limited to the democratisation of politics, securing human rights, and the management of resources. The parties are expected to arrive at a Final Framework Agreement (FFA) that addresses the transitional stresses and provide a roadmap for a democratic, peaceful, and prosperous South Sudan. The path to a Final negotiated agreement requires that both parties publicly commit to the full range of provisions set forth in Article 21; demonstrate tangible political will to reach a consensus unaligned to the structure of the agreement; make joint commitments to implement the structure and articles of the roadmap on an urgently expedited timeline; and implement the necessary steps to secure the minimal requirements for a final Roadmap agreement. The process going forward to ensure that the political leadership and sectors of the population come to a shared understanding of the articles in the Road Map are likely to be burried under the weight of the obstructionist tactics in both parties to this Roadmap inked in 2015.
